by studying the older ones.

00:41:38.430 --> 00:41:43.370 align:middle line:90%


00:41:43.370 --> 00:41:46.720 align:middle line:84%
Could this be a leap in the
evolution of the species?

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:50.260 align:middle line:84%
An end to the vicious circle
of coming into the world

00:41:50.260 --> 00:41:53.240 align:middle line:90%
with no adult to learn from.

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:56.450 align:middle line:84%
If so, the octopuses'
future seems limitless.

00:41:56.450 --> 00:42:01.760 align:middle line:90%


00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:05.180 align:middle line:84%
Back in Naples, Professor
Graziano Fiorito,

00:42:05.180 --> 00:42:07.940 align:middle line:84%
a pioneer in the study
of the behavioral biology

00:42:07.940 --> 00:42:11.110 align:middle line:84%
of the octopus, in collaboration
with David Edelman,

00:42:11.110 --> 00:42:13.990 align:middle line:84%
wants to put their
theories into practice.

00:42:13.990 --> 00:42:17.020 align:middle line:84%
They want to demonstrate that
the new generation of octopus

00:42:17.020 --> 00:42:19.000 align:middle line:90%
is now learning how to learn.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:23.520 align:middle line:90%


00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:25.330 align:middle line:84%
>>We got an idea
for an experiment

00:42:25.330 --> 00:42:27.202 align:middle line:84%
when we were watching
a Cousteau film.

00:42:27.202 --> 00:42:31.500 align:middle line:90%


00:42:31.500 --> 00:42:34.160 align:middle line:10%
Cousteau showed an octopus
opening a sealed glass

00:42:34.160 --> 00:42:37.440 align:middle line:10%
container to get to his food.

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:40.990 align:middle line:10%
In his case, the food was a
lobster, whereas we use crabs.

00:42:40.990 --> 00:42:45.430 align:middle line:90%


00:42:45.430 --> 00:42:48.870 align:middle line:84%
We wondered what would happen
if we placed two octopuses face

00:42:48.870 --> 00:42:52.380 align:middle line:84%
to face, one who knows
how to open the container,

00:42:52.380 --> 00:42:54.030 align:middle line:90%
and the other, who doesn't.

00:42:54.030 --> 00:42:56.050 align:middle line:84%
We wanted to know
if one octopus could

00:42:56.050 --> 00:42:57.680 align:middle line:90%
learn by observing the other.

00:42:57.680 --> 00:43:02.800 align:middle line:90%


00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:07.060 align:middle line:84%
We created a box
with three openings.

00:43:07.060 --> 00:43:10.270 align:middle line:84%
The difference between the
three openings is how they open.

00:43:10.270 --> 00:43:15.350 align:middle line:84%
With the first opening,
the cover simply lifts off.

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:18.530 align:middle line:84%
With the second opening, you
have to twist open the cover.

00:43:18.530 --> 00:43:23.480 align:middle line:84%
You have to twist it first,
and then pull it off.

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:25.810 align:middle line:84%
And the last cover
also pulls off,

00:43:25.810 --> 00:43:29.370 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't come
off completely.

00:43:29.370 --> 00:43:32.310 align:middle line:84%
We place a crab in
the box, and then we

00:43:32.310 --> 00:43:33.370 align:middle line:90%
wait to see what happens.

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:39.930 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.930 --> 00:43:42.520 align:middle line:84%
>>In the lab, the tanks
are divided into two

00:43:42.520 --> 00:43:44.270 align:middle line:90%
by a glass wall.

00:43:44.270 --> 00:43:47.670 align:middle line:84%
A box with a crab in
it is placed in one.

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:50.440 align:middle line:84%
Also in that tank is
Candide, an octopus

00:43:50.440 --> 00:43:55.000 align:middle line:84%
that was caught by a
fisherman just that morning.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:58.760 align:middle line:84%
Candide sees the crab,
but doesn't react.

00:43:58.760 --> 00:44:01.670 align:middle line:84%
This is exactly what the
researchers expected.

00:44:01.670 --> 00:44:03.110 align:middle line:90%
The experiment can proceed.

00:44:03.110 --> 00:44:13.450 align:middle line:90%


00:44:13.450 --> 00:44:16.240 align:middle line:84%
In the other side of the
tank the same kind of box

00:44:16.240 --> 00:44:19.780 align:middle line:84%
is given to an octopus that
has spent a few days in the lab

00:44:19.780 --> 00:44:23.500 align:middle line:84%
and has learned how to get
into the multiple opening box.

00:44:23.500 --> 00:44:26.180 align:middle line:84%
This octopus is
called the trainee.

00:44:26.180 --> 00:44:29.415 align:middle line:84%
It immediately starts to open
the box to get at the prey.

00:44:29.415 --> 00:44:39.290 align:middle line:90%


00:44:39.290 --> 00:44:41.340 align:middle line:90%
Candide watches the trainee.

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:44.680 align:middle line:90%
His curiosity is aroused.

00:44:44.680 --> 00:44:47.620 align:middle line:84%
The trainee isn't
wasting its time.

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:50.280 align:middle line:84%
Candide is visibly
excited and is clearly

00:44:50.280 --> 00:44:53.680 align:middle line:84%
trying to understand what
the octopus is doing.

00:44:53.680 --> 00:44:56.550 align:middle line:84%
Finally, the trainee
octopus opens the box

00:44:56.550 --> 00:44:58.570 align:middle line:90%
and seizes the crab.

00:44:58.570 --> 00:45:01.860 align:middle line:84%
Has Candide really learned
by observing the trainee?

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:04.210 align:middle line:84%
Will he prove the
Capri theory right?

00:45:04.210 --> 00:45:07.730 align:middle line:90%


00:45:07.730 --> 00:45:10.830 align:middle line:84%
It's a crucial moment
for Graziano and David.

00:45:10.830 --> 00:45:12.520 align:middle line:90%
They won't have to wait long.

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:18.060 align:middle line:90%


00:45:18.060 --> 00:45:20.420 align:middle line:84%
Now the glass panel
between the two tanks

00:45:20.420 --> 00:45:23.200 align:middle line:84%
is covered over,
preventing the octopuses

00:45:23.200 --> 00:45:24.890 align:middle line:90%
from seeing each other.

00:45:24.890 --> 00:45:28.730 align:middle line:84%
Candide is left alone
with the problem.

00:45:28.730 --> 00:45:30.060 align:middle line:90%
Is he going to succeed?

00:45:30.060 --> 00:45:33.920 align:middle line:90%


00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:37.760 align:middle line:84%
Without hesitating, Candide
grapples with the box

00:45:37.760 --> 00:45:41.130 align:middle line:84%
and manages to get it open
in barely a few seconds.

00:45:41.130 --> 00:45:44.170 align:middle line:84%
He's observed and
he's understood.

00:45:44.170 --> 00:45:46.760 align:middle line:84%
The experiment is
repeated dozens of times,

00:45:46.760 --> 00:45:49.600 align:middle line:84%
and the box is placed
in different positions.

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:52.460 align:middle line:84%
The octopus always opens
it on the same side,

00:45:52.460 --> 00:45:55.670 align:middle line:84%
using the same opening,
showing that he didn't simply

00:45:55.670 --> 00:45:57.530 align:middle line:90%
learn to imitate a movement.

00:45:57.530 --> 00:46:01.270 align:middle line:84%
He really understood
what had to be done.

00:46:01.270 --> 00:46:04.920 align:middle line:84%
It seems that the octopus is
about to take a leap ahead

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:07.190 align:middle line:90%
in the evolutionary scheme.

00:46:07.190 --> 00:46:11.220 align:middle line:84%
There may be no holding back
its formidable intelligence.

00:46:11.220 --> 00:46:14.100 align:middle line:84%
Is this the start of a
Hollywood horror movie?

00:46:14.100 --> 00:46:30.004 align:middle line:90%


00:46:30.004 --> 00:46:33.483 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:46:33.483 --> 00:46:36.500 align:middle line:90%


00:46:36.500 --> 00:46:40.343 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps it's best to think of
it this way-- under the sea,

00:46:40.343 --> 00:46:44.670 align:middle line:84%
a new form of higher
intelligence is taking shape.

00:46:44.670 --> 00:46:47.110 align:middle line:84%
It isn't going to
happen overnight.

00:46:47.110 --> 00:46:49.940 align:middle line:84%
Hundreds of thousands
of years will probably

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:52.710 align:middle line:84%
have to pass before
the octopuses' thinking

00:46:52.710 --> 00:46:55.370 align:middle line:90%
powers can rival ours.

00:46:55.370 --> 00:46:57.735 align:middle line:84%
Nature has all the
time in the world.

00:46:57.735 --> 00:47:00.972 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:47:00.972 --> 00:47:14.920 align:middle line:90%


00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:18.030 align:middle line:84%
Who knows, the next
conquerors of the Earth

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:21.250 align:middle line:84%
won't have to come
from outer space.

00:47:21.250 --> 00:47:23.890 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to make
friends with them.

00:47:23.890 --> 00:47:25.770 align:middle line:90%
After all, they're already here.

00:47:25.770 --> 00:47:29.120 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:47:29.120 --> 00:48:46.058 align:middle line:90%